Univariate Plots Section

Below are the names of all initial variables in the dataset, general information on the dataset and all variables. In addition a summary is produced that shows basic statistics on each variables. Although quality was accessed on a scale of 1-10, it is important to note that all wines in this dataset were rated between 3-8, with a mean of 5.636. Since quality is an ordinal value, mode might be a more accurate representation of quality which is 5.

Number of columns and rows

The dataset containts 1599 wines, marked by number in the first column of the dataset, followed by 11 measured properties, and a quality rating.

I plotted all variables in the wine dataset below to get an idea of their

distributions. I changed banwidths on most of the plots, and the scale on

some so that more detail could be seen.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  wine$fixed.acidity
## W = 0.94203, p-value < 2.2e-16

There appear to be a few wines that have higher fixed acidity than others, but for the most part this data appears normally distributed. However, the mean is 8.32, a bit higher than the median of 7.90, suggesting it is slightly skewed to the right. A Shapiro Wilks test fails to reject the nullhypothesis that the data is normal.

The volatile acidity looks to be quite consistent. I wouldnt say the data is normally distributed as I see two, or maybe arguably three peaks in this plot, however the mean and median are very close at .5200 and .5278 respectively. There is also an outlier near 1.6, that is quite far from all other measurements.

This data appears to be skewed to the right, however it has a couple of interesting aspects to it. It looks like there are many entries that are 0.0, .25, or .50 in the dataset (shown by the three bars that elevate above all the rest of the data). This could be because of the way that citric acid is recorded when measured. Interestingly, although the data is continuous, that aspect gives it a ordinal quality. Again I there is an outlier far from others, this time at 1.00.

Because of the extreme outliers in these two plots I took at look at their boxplots and found the wines with the associated values. Neither are from the same wine.

Because of outliers in the data, I decided to plot the residual sugar and

chlorides on a logarithmic scale in order to take a look at the data in a

normal distribution.

The log scale shows that residual sugar in red wine leans toward a normally distribution and residual sugar is usually consistent, other than a large amount of outliers from the normal distribution. The mean is pulled to 2.539 by the outliers, while the median is 2.200.

The boxplot visualizes the mass amount of outliers from the otherwise normal distribution.

The log scale on sulfur dioxide shows a much clearer picture of the data, showing that most of the data lies between .05 and .15, with a fair amount of data above .15 that are not included in the normal distribuation of data. The median is at .07900 and the mean is at .08747, pulled to the right by the outliers.

Like residual sugar, the boxplot demonstrates the large amount of outliers.

## [1] 1245

Free sulfur dioxide is skewed to the right. The mean is far from the mode of 38.00 at 46.47. There is a max of 289, again a different wine from others I looked up with outliers thus far.

## [1] 1082

Total sulfur dioxide is also skewed to the right. The mean is 46.47, median is 38.00 and the max is 289.00 showing a similar distribuation to free sulfur dioxides. The wines with the max values however are different.

Because the plots look similar, I ran a correlation test and found a value of .668 which shows a moderate correlation.

Density appears to be normally distributed. The median and mean are similar at .9968 and .9967 respectively.

pH appears normally distributed, with most wines falling inbetween 3.0 and 3.5, with an outlier at 4.010 shown by the max. The median and mean are close though at 3.310 and 3.311.

Sulphates shows slight skew to the right, but for the most part looks normally distributed with almost all data falling inbetween .5 and 1.0.The mean is slightly higher at .6581, compared to the median at .6200.

Most wines in this dataset fall between 9 and 10 percent alcohol by volume, steadily tapering off to around 13 percent. Wines that have under 9 percent or over 13 percent alcohol are rarer in this dataset. The mean is at 10.42 with the meadian just a bit lower at 10.20.

The plot below shows that most wines in this dataset are rated as 5 or 6 in quality. That leads me to wonder what correlations can be found that are associated with lower (3/4) and higher (7/8) ratings. Are there properties of wine that are predictors of lower and higher rated wine?

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 wines in the dataset with 13 variables. One variable, X, assigns the wine a number. Quality is a rating, with a minimum of 3 and max of 8 in this dataset (rated on a scale of 0-10, very bad - very excellent). The other 11 variables are chemical properties of the wine.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I think the main variable of interest in the dataset is quality. The question of interest is finding if any of the chemical properties can be used as strong predictors of the quality of a wine. Because the taste of wine is complex, and a balance of properties is important, I assume I will be looking for a combination of properties that affect quality. My initial interest is in fixed acidity, residual sugar, and alcohol.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Since most wines fall into quality ratings of 5 and 6 and thus we could call these average, it is possible that cutting the data set into low ratings (3/4) and high ratings (7/8) could be a way to look for properties that stand out.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Bouncing off the idea above I created a variable that groups the ratings in low, average, and high.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change

the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I thought the residual sugar, chlorides, and free sulfur dioxide plots were all being effected by long tails. I performed a log function to adjust the plot closer to a normal distribution. After adjusting binwidths as well on all the plots, it looked like most chemical properties have a normal distribution or are skewed to the right. Citric acid is the only property that looks sporatic. The distribution is skewed to the right overall, but many values are at 0.00, 0.25, or .50. This may be a product of the way citric acid is recorded in many wines.

I ran a few correlation test on variables that I thought might be correlated with the quality rating of wine. I found alcohol to have the highest correlation at .47. Surprisingly, residual sugar has effectively no correlation to the quality ratings of wine. Volatile acidity is negatively correlated with quality at a value of -0.39. Some quick research showed me that excessive volatile acids are associated with unpleasing aromos and poor taste. I also found that acids are an important part of the overall character of wine so I want to further explore citric acid which shows a correlation with quality of .22. I also found it interesting that sulphates produced a correlation of .25 since to my understanding this is a perservative used to stop the fermentation process.

Below I produced the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient test

among variables of interest and produced a table as well across all variables

of interest.

Bivariate Plots Section

I first ran a scatterplot on quality vs. alcohol, but I found a boxplot is a more useful visualization of the relationship. It is clear that higher rated wines have more alcohol.

The grouped variable I created gives an even clearer picture. The low and average buckets have similar distributions, however the highly rated wines have higher alcohol, with the IQR of wines rated high almost completely outside of the range of wines rated as low and average. It should be noted though that there are a few outliers in the average group with high percentages of alcohol. At a 95% confidence level, the Pearson correlation coefficient between quality and alcohol is 0.4761663

The boxplot below shows a visualization of residual sugars lack of effect on quality ratings. The outliers in the quality ratings display the variability of sugar levels within quality ratings. Along with a Pearson correlcation value of 0.0137, I am concluding that residual sugar levels, within an expected (or normal) range do not have a meaningful effect on quality ratings in this dataset. Pearson correlation coefficient between quality and alcohol is 0.01373164

Here is the same group of plots, except using the original ratings. I think for the most part, my grouped ratings tell a story that is easier to see. It is interesting that the clearest trend that emerges from these plots is the relationship betweeen volatile acidity and quality.

A bivariate analysis developed my features of interest. Alcohol made the list with its strong effect on quality. where I originally thought fixed.acid would be an interesting factor (based soley on my lack of expertise), I now see that citric acid is a better predictor of quality. I found that sugar does not have the effect I thought it might, however volatile acidity and sulphate levels proved to be chemical properties that seem to have an effect on quality ratings in this dataset.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Alcohol is the strongest relationship I found.

summary(wine$alcohol) # Multivariate Plots Section

I created a variable that defines the alcohol in buckets of low, medium, or high. This plot shows the median value volatile acidity within each quality by alcohol group. Here, with quality levels of 5 and 6, the alcohol groups have similar volatile acidity, where there is more variance at other levels. Among the lowest quality rating charted (3), the volatile acidity is much lower than that of the highest rating charted (8).

This chart shows the median suplphate measurements across quality ratings by alcohol groups. The chart shows a trend that is easier to see than the previous where regardless of alcohol group, the quality rating tends to increase as the amount of citric acid increases. Especially among medium abv wines, the relationship looks linear. There is also a trend among groups, where the highest abv has lowest citric acid measurements among quality groups 5-8.

This chart shows the median sulphate levels across quality ratings by alcohol groups. The grouping among quality ratings 4-7 pops out first. There appears to be a linear relationship and the alcohol groups are have similar sulphate measurements across the ratings. The lowest and highest ratings (3-8), have more variance, especially at rating 8.

This chart plots each wine based on their alcohol and sulphate levels, colored by quality rating. Since there isnt a lot of data on the highest and lowest ratings, it is difficult to see any trends among those ratings. Of the lower quality wines, I can see points despersed across alcohol levels, at lower sulphate measurements. There is a grouping of those wines with quality level 5 trending toward lower sulphate and alcohol levels. It seems that wines rated at quality 6 and 7 tend to have higher alcohol levels, yet are dispersed across sulphate levels, mostly within the range of .5 and 1.0.

Here I changed the y axis to volatile acidity. I would have expected to see less dispersion across volatile acidity here across quality ratings. Again those wines rated 5 are tending toward lower abv. I do see lower quality wines plotted at higher volatile acidity and the highest quality wines plotted at lower volatile acidity, however average rated wines show a lot of variance among volatile acidity measurements.

When using the grouped quality ratings variable, a trend is easier to see. Higher rated wines dispersed across all abv levels, tend to lower volatile acidity. Average tend to have lower alcohol levels and have more variance across volatile acidity. I am surprised that I am not seeing low quality wines grouped together.

This chart with citric.acid on the y scale shows a lot of dispersion across citric acid levels, yet again alcohol is grouped lower within a quality rating of 5. By now we can start to see that most wines rated 5 in this data set, regardless of other factors will mostly have alcohol levels inbetween 8-10 and those rated 7 or 8 will mostly have abv of 10+.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms

of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

&

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

As alcohol seems to have the most significant impact on quality ratings, I split it up into 3 groups: low, medium, and high alohol content so I could see how these groups interacted with other variables of interest.

Through these plots I noticed that of those wines in the group with high alcohol, none of these wines received a rating of 3.

I was particularly interested in how volatile acidity would interact with these groups as it seems to be a significant factor in wine quality ratings as well. I noticed that the high alcohol group had lower acidity within all quality ratings. Those wines that have high volatile acidity content also have many more quality ratings of 3.

I also plotted citric acid among the 3 groups. This plot seems to show a relationship with higher ratings and higher citric acid levels across all groups. Again though, the high alcohol group was least affected by citric acid levels vs quality ratings. Other than at quality rating 4, the high alcohol group had less citric acid at every rating (5-8) vs the low and medium groups.

Next I plotted suplphate levels by quality v quality rating by alcohol groups. The relationship was very similar across all quality ratings other than 8. At a rating of 8, it seems that wines with lower alcohol had higher levels of suplphates.

Throughout the scatterplots, the strongest trend visualized was that average rated wines tend to have lower alcohol and higher rated wines have higher alcohol levels.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset?

Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

Because the relationship between quality and alcohol are plotted within 6 quality ratings (3-8), I found it difficult to see if the relationship is linear, although they dont look far from it.

In this group of charts, the points represent the median alcohol level among each quality rating. There are relationships that seem to break out among quality ratings, for example among quality ratings 6-8 within alcohol measurements. Volatile acidity looks to have a linear relationship across ratings and with its Pearson correlation coefficient of -.39 might be a moderate predictor in a linear model.

I attempted a simple model that test the relationship between quality and 4 other variables. Past alcohol and volatile acidity, the model doesnt appear to predict much. With an r-squared value of .3, I do not see this model as dependably predictive.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

### Description One This boxplot shows a clear difference between the three quality groups (low, average, high). Those wines have been rated a 7 or 8 in quality ratings have a much higher mean of abv. There are some wines in the average group that have high alcohol, shown as outliers on the boxplot, however this vizualization shows that most wines that have a higher rating will have more alcohol than those that are rated as low or average.

Plot Two

Description Two

This boxplot is a good respresentation of the negative correlation that volatile acidity has with quality rating. It is clear that as lower rated wines have higher levels of volatile acidity, while higher rated wines have lower volatile acidity. Those wines rated 7 or 8 have similar levels. It can also be seen that among lower quality ratings, there more of a range among volatile acidity measurements, but as quality ratings increase, the range becomes more compact, with less outliers as well. If you told me one wine has a volatile acidity of .4 and the another .8, I would tell you I would like to drink the one with .4.

Plot Three

Description Three

I found this plot interesting because it emerged that sulphate levels are quite consistent across quality ratings among alcohol groups. No matter if a wine has a low, medium, or high abv, among quality ratings of 4-7, wines follow a distinct pattern. Only at the rating of 8 is there divergence.

Reflection

This exercise gave me a better understanding of how trends and variables to explore can emerge through visualization. I was able to use a correlation computation to find out which variables might be worth exploring, however it is the plots that help answer the subtleties of how one variable affects another. I liked the idea of grouping properties of interest in this exercise to help dig deeper into how the the property affected quality ratings. This project did reinforce the importance of running statistical test. I think visualizations of data can be exciting and lead you to believe that a particular variable is affecting another much more than it actually is. I honestly expected even my simple linear model to show higher r-squared values than it did.

If I were going to further explore this group I would want a lot more wines rated low (3 or lower) and high (8 and higher) so I could have more confidence in my findings.

## 
##   3   4   5   6   7   8 
##  10  53 681 638 199  18

This data set only has 10 wines rated as a 3 and 18 rated as an 8. That makes a good argument for splitting the quality ratings into 3 groups as I did to draw conclusions, but one could be less confident about drawing conclusions from observations within the wines rated as 3 or 8. Then again, using the groups gives less of a chance to see unique trends that emerge among specific quality ratings.
